    "text": "The necessity of translating long-term memory into embodied plans arises only when an agent architecture explicitly includes a long-term memory module for state representation.",
    "topic": "Dependency on architectural choice"
  },
  {
    "text": "Partial observability and overwritten world states can be addressed by reactive policies that directly map sensor inputs to actions without explicitly constructing long-term memory representations.",
    "topic": "Alternative solution existence"
  },
  {
    "text": "The WorldLines paper describes its memory-to-plan translation as a technique for handling long-horizon tasks under partial observability, not as an inherent problem that all embodied agents must solve.",
    "topic": "Scope of the WorldLines claim"
  },
  {
    "text": "The challenge of translating long-term memory into embodied plans is a subproblem of the broader partial observability challenge, specifically for agents that use explicit, updateable world-state representations over time.",
    "topic": "Hierarchical classification"
  }
]
